<div id="review_15510716" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/15510716" />
    <a title="Margit" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/909733-margit"><img alt="Margit" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1224095069p2/909733.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/15510716?book_show_action=true">Feb 15, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Margit" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Margit" href="/user/show/909733-margit">Margit</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Alison and Nicky</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer15510716" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12631959167734916342">Appointment in Samarra is an American Classic by John O&apos;Hara. He describes the life of a young man in small town America before the Depression who has it all. When he makes a big mistake on Christmas his downward spiral is aided by people and events and shows that it is rather difficult to evade one&apos;s fate. This is also implied by the Arabian parable in the beginning of the book.<br/>The book is very well written and , although it is depressing, I enjoyed it very much.</span>
  <span id="freeText12631959167734916342" style="display:none">Appointment in Samarra is an American Classic by John O'Hara. He describes the life of a young man in small town America before the Depression who has it all. When he makes a big mistake on Christmas his downward spiral is aided by people and events and shows that it is rather difficult to evade one's fate. This is also implied by the Arabian parable in the beginning of the book.<br />The book is very well written and , although it is depressing, I enjoyed it very much.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12631959167734916342" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


