    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_79228639" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/79228639" />
    <a title="K.D. Absolutely" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2156200-k-d-absolutely"><img alt="K.D. Absolutely" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471967140p2/2156200.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/79228639?book_show_action=true">Nov 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K.D. Absolutely" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K.D. Absolutely" href="/user/show/2156200-k-d-absolutely">K.D. Absolutely</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780394711928" href="/book/show/857127.Appointment_in_Samarra">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2156200-k-d-absolutely?shelf=100-best-english-novel">100-best-english-novel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2156200-k-d-absolutely?shelf=american">american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer79228639" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15011296634295955891">This novel is one of the Modern Library&apos;s 100 Best English novels of the 20th century. I had this in my to-be-read shelf for half a decade before I finally cracked this open. A favorite local author of mine, Abdon M. Balde mentioned this in his &quot;Kislap&quot; anthology of short-short stories. He said that the length of this book is exact: not a word is unnecessary.<br/><br/>So, I checked and yes, I agree. &quot;Appointment in Samarra&quot; is a light read, short and easily digestible. It tells the story of Julian English</span>
  <span id="freeText15011296634295955891" style="display:none">This novel is one of the Modern Library's 100 Best English novels of the 20th century. I had this in my to-be-read shelf for half a decade before I finally cracked this open. A favorite local author of mine, Abdon M. Balde mentioned this in his "Kislap" anthology of short-short stories. He said that the length of this book is exact: not a word is unnecessary.<br /><br />So, I checked and yes, I agree. "Appointment in Samarra" is a light read, short and easily digestible. It tells the story of Julian English, a 30-year old young entrepreneur in the USA during the 30's. English has a beautiful wife, Caroline and his own business selling Cadillac cars. He is the son of a medical doctor who is one of the respected and rich men in the Gibbsville, a fictitious town in Pennsylvania. <br /><br />The story covers a span of only 3 days that start on Christmas Day. Only three days that are full of events, dialogues and conversations. I have not had anything, even how remote, similar to those during Christmastime. After all, English's Lantenengo Street crowd isn't my crowd and my Christmas is normally spent in with my in-laws (the previous day and the early morning of the day) or sleeping until early afternoon. Then if the following day is a working day, I normally go back to work. My point is: the life of Julian English is totally different from mine so the book is a tad unrelatable for an Asian reader like me whose living in the 22nd century.<br /><br />However, it is the writing that made me enjoy reading this book. The omniscient narrator does not tell all. Then the stream-of-consciousness towards the last part of the story was just fascinatingly brilliant. The narration is one for the books for it seemingly plain but if you really pay attention to what's happening and the way you are learning how you come to that conclusion, it will just dawn on you that you are forming conclusions like a normal human being. Then, you'll feel sorry for English even though at the start, or for the most part of the story, he is some kind of brat that you don't feel any sympathy for. Until, the last of the story, of course. It will just surprise you and then you'll feel sympathy like you never felt for any fictional American character in the pre-Depression era.<br /><br />Overall, a nice read and a book that I am proud to have read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15011296634295955891" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


